Simple ways to help your child deal with tantrums
I have often seen parents view a child's outbursts of anger as wrong and abnormal.
When a child expresses his anger openly, we don't know how to react, says psychologist Ekaterina Kess.
He suggests that we talk a little about those natural human emotions - anger and resentment - that we all experience from time to time.
Aggression is physical action directed against another person, usually when we are angry.
When we adults get angry, upset, we usually know what's happening to us and how to deal with it.
We can express, repress, suppress, bottle up, tell our friends or other loved ones, kick the sofa, smoke a cigarette (not the best way to let off steam!), take a shower, pound the table, or do other things that we normally would not do.
We don't take our aggression out on others because we have all these other ways of dealing with these emotions.
When kids get angry, they don't know what's happening to them, what to call it, or how to deal with it.
They may say things like, "Go away!" "You're an idiot!" "You're a bad mother!" "I hate you!" "I'm not going to hang out with you!"
Children are literally alive, they're fully present in the here and now, they're spontaneous and genuine in their expression, and they're often in the throes of a range of emotions.
It is vital that parents not stifle, shame, or discourage their children from expressing their emotions, including anger.
