German researchers debate the number of "victims of the Berlin Wall".
A new study suggests that the death toll on the borders of the former Communist East Germany may be much higher than previously thought, but doubts remain.
According to figures released Wednesday by the Berlin Wall Museum at Checkpoint Charlie, between 1945 and 1989, Communist authorities murdered 1,841 people who tried to escape from areas under their control at the border between the Allied zone and what later became West Germany.
The museum has been tracking border-related deaths for years and periodically revises the death toll.
This year, 11 more deaths have been added to the list, including that of a six-year-old boy who drowned as his family tried to reach West Germany through what was then Czechoslovakia and Hungary.
Among the new victims of the Berlin Wall are Soviet army deserters.
"The full extent of the damage caused by the twin evils of communism and socialism has not yet been fully documented", admits museum director Alexandra Hildebrandt.
"Our task is to ensure that the graves of those who died trying to escape from the Communist-controlled country are collected and preserved", Hildebrandt said in a statement.
However, other researchers have already questioned the new figures.
"The figure of 1841 is not convincing", claims Johannes Statz, an expert on East German history at the Free University of Berlin, in an interview with the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung.
He and other researchers at the Free University of Berlin are currently reviewing possible suspicious deaths at the border, and so far they have only been able to confirm 260 cases.
Researchers previously estimated that at the Berlin Wall alone, 138 people were murdered by the Communists.
Taking into account the number of people who died trying to flee across the Baltic Sea or to reach the West through the territory of neighbouring countries, the State estimates that the number of victims could reach about a thousand.
However, it is still significantly lower than in 1841.
One of the reasons for the different numbers of casualties could be the different methodologies.
The Checkpoint Charlie museum also lists all suicides by East German border guards, whether or not they were directly related to their service.
The museum also records deaths that are not directly related to violence.
"If seniors in their 70's and 80's die of heart attacks after collapsing at the border", it must be the result of this "killer frontier", says Hildebrante.
However, the State believes that a distinction must be made between elderly people who may have died as a result of the abuse they suffered and those whose deaths were caused by long waits in hot weather on a bus at the border.
Regardless, counting the victims is not easy because the East German Communist authorities did not keep such statistics and researchers have to dig through scattered archives, according to the State.
However, the State group has recently published new documents and may soon release new casualty estimates.
