Māris Kuņickis, Production Director of Latvenergo, said that concern for the environment is one of the cornerstones of the group's sustainable development.
'Every activity in the protection and reproduction of fish resources is aimed at environmentally friendly actions in close cooperation with the Bior scientific institute, both by breeding and releasing juvenile fish in the Daugava basin and by implementing other activities,' said Kunickis.
This year, more than 600 000 yearling salmon and sea trout will be released into the Danube estuary.
From the second year onwards, the fry are marked by cutting the fathead minnow before release.
Today's shipment includes 25,000 baby salmon weighing an average of 31.3 grams.
The introduction of juveniles and larvae into the Danube and its basin water bodies shall be carried out annually on the basis of scientifically sound species composition and numbers.
The restoration of fish stocks in the Danube River and its basin shall be carried out by the Bior in accordance with the legislation, based on an expert assessment of the damage caused to fish stocks as a result of Latvenergo's economic activities and providing a conclusion on the compensatory measures to be taken to ensure the diversity of fish stocks.
The State Environmental Service, in turn, decides on the amount and form of compensation on the basis of this expert report.
Latvenergo's annual compensation for the fish stock recovery programme is EUR 1 035 000.
In the spring of 2016, Latvenergo, in cooperation with the 'Mēs zivīm' association, will install 400 artificial fish spawning nests in the Daugava near Kaibalas and Ikšilas for the fifth year.
Cooperation with the association in promoting natural spawning of fish is an additional initiative supported by Latvenergo in the framework of the fish stock recovery programme.
The construction of artificial nests in the reservoir is an important measure contributing to the conservation and reproduction of fish resources in the Danube.
