A French court has rejected a request to demolish shops in the Jungle refugee camp.
A French court has rejected a claim by Calais authorities to demolish dozens of self-built shops and restaurants in the "Jungle" camp, home to several thousand refugees.
At a court hearing in Calais this week, the authorities said the state should demolish 72 home-grown shops where people in the camp sell things like cigarettes and energy drinks, haircuts, tea for 50 cents (40p) and simple meals for a few euros in home-grown restaurants.
The prefect's office in Calais stated that these self-established businesses had to be dismantled because they formed a shadow economy and did not pay taxes, and posed fire and health risks.
The representatives of the humanitarian group explained to the court that these small businesses are essential because the food provided by the government and support groups does not meet the needs of the camp, where the number of inhabitants continues to grow.
They also pointed out that self-help stores and restaurants often offer free shelter and food to those who need it most.
The Court of Lille ruled that there was no legal basis for the eviction of people who had set up 72 self-built shops, but it understood the concerns of the Prefect of Calais.
Judge Jean-François Mollet said that food, cafes, and restaurants play a greater role than simply providing food for people living in "extremely poor conditions".
He pointed out that these places are peaceful meeting places for refugees and volunteers.
One of the sites at risk of demolition is the camp's Jungle Book Kids café, which provides more than 200 free meals a day, English and French language classes and shelter advice to hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
A letter to the Guardian said that closing the cafe "would be a disaster for these children, some as young as eight".
On Friday, two charities, Aid to Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants, reported that the number of people living in the Jungle camp had risen to 9,000, the highest figure since the summer surge.
