In the final four minutes, Jerry Tuwai also extended the lead with a touchdown on the right wing.
The score was 12 to nothing, and the British team had barely touched the ball.
Mitchell's brilliant power play prevented the typical Leonie Nakarawa from scoring three points, but it only slightly affected Fiji's result.
In the seventh minute of the game, Jas Veremalua scored a touchdown in the right corner, extending the lead over Great Britain to 17-0.
After the break, Nakarava extended his lead to more than a minute left in the first half.
Vatemo Ravouvou avoided some clumsy British force tactics and crossed the line to score.
The touchdown made it 29 to nothing.
It seemed that Fiji was born to play rugby sevens while the British were still learning.
As a matter of fact, it is true.
The British team made a dramatic turnaround at half-time, breaking the Fijian line... for a full four minutes, which was good by first-half standards, until Joshua Tuisova, after a fantastic team effort, scored a few more points for Fiji.
Dan Norton scored the winning points for the British team with a touchdown in the left corner to make the score 36-7, but the game was already lost as the South Sea Islanders sang, waved flags, and danced in the stands.
One cannot help but admire the happy-go-lucky attitude of the Fijians.
Matt William made Fiji's victory even sweeter with another late touchdown.
When the final whistle blew, Fiji could celebrate, but the British sat on the grass in defeat.
In the first half of the day, Fiji defeated Japan 20-5 in the semi-finals, while the British were ahead of South Africa, where in a very fierce battle both teams won on the ground and the South Africans lost by only a few points.
