In Spain, the prospects for reducing the budget deficit are threatened by the inability to form a government.
A month ago, on 12 July, the European Commission (EC) concluded that Spain and Portugal had not taken sufficient measures to reduce their budget deficits to the 3% of GDP required by the euro area.
It is estimated that, despite the austerity measures implemented, Portugal's budget deficit reached 4.4% of GDP at the end of last year, compared with 5.1% in Spain.
However, the European Commission decided not to impose economic sanctions on both countries, while setting fiscal targets for the near future.
One of the reasons why the EC did not impose sanctions on these two countries is the growing Euroscepticism in many EU countries.
Additional sanctions would only increase this negative sentiment.
Critics, however, point out that the EC is inconsistent in its decisions, agreeing common rules at the outset and then failing to apply them in practice.
For example, Jens Weidmann, president of the German Bundesbank, has pointed out that Europe is losing its self-confidence by creating the impression that European Union rules are advisory rather than binding.
The Commission has now proposed, and all Member States have agreed, to extend the deadline for the correction of budgetary deficits until the end of this year for Portugal and until 2018 for Spain.
The European Commission promises to review the progress made by both countries in the coming months, while pointing out that both Spain and Portugal must be ready to introduce further austerity measures if circumstances so require.
Initial forecasts indicate that the targets set for Portugal could be achieved on time and that the budget deficit could be reduced to 2,5% of GDP already this year.
This means that the government will have to implement austerity measures amounting to 0,25% of GDP this year as part of the stability programme.
These measures should be included in this year's budget, with additional attention being paid to controlling the cost of procurement of goods and services.
In the case of Spain, the situation is much more complex.
The budget deficit is to be reduced to 4,6% of GDP this year, 3,1% next year and 2,2% in 2018.
In addition, consolidation measures should amount to 0,5% of GDP each year for the following two years.
Achieving these objectives is made particularly difficult by the fact that Spanish political parties have been unable to agree on a government for eight months and by the growing possibility that Spain may have to hold early parliamentary elections for the third time in a year.
