The most popular party remains the People's Party, led by current Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, which would again get less than 33% of the vote.
Only the Socialists have slightly increased their popularity, while the anti-austerity parties Podemos and Ciudadanos have slightly decreased.
The PP wants the Socialists and Ciudadanos to join the government this month, otherwise it will not be able to adopt and submit the 2017 draft budget to the European Commission for approval by mid-October.
According to Rafael Hernando, a member of the Popular Party parliamentary group, if a government is not formed and elections are held for a third time, Spain will become the laughingstock of Europe.
The cleanliness of the bathing areas in the Gulf of Riga is critical.
After surveying the beaches for the fifth year, activists concluded that unfortunately the number of items found is increasing year by year, and visitors are largely to blame.
