"The main source is the beachgoers themselves, as more than half of the total amount of waste is plastic, all kinds of waste, starting with bags, pieces of plastic that are already in the process of decomposing, they can no longer be identified, and cigarette butts, bottles, corks", says Ulme.
Among the dirtiest beaches are those in Riga.
In Daugavpils, for example, an average of almost 800 pieces of waste is collected every hundred meters, which is a critical amount.
Campaigners also explain that smoking is rampant and that warning or prohibition signs are not posted everywhere.
"The average figures for all three bathing areas in Riga - Daugavpils, Vakarbuļi and Vecāķi - are unfortunately high and far exceed the desired goal, which Latvia seems to be moving towards, to reduce the number of waste units to 135 units by 2020", concludes the environmentalist.
The cleaning of swimming pools in Riga is done every day, even twice on the hottest days of summer, explains Uģis Vidauskis, a member of the council.
However, dealing with unclean visitors is not easy.
We come back to the question of the culture of these people.
"Those who gossip, drink, smoke, and do all the other things you're not supposed to do, even the special signs don't work on them", says Vidauskis.
Therefore, Vidauskis urges visitors to the bathing areas to report the pollutants to the police.
