Before the 40th anniversary of Liv, the legendary rock band can be introduced at an exhibition in Liepāja.
The exhibition will feature various objects that characterize "Livas" - photographs that are arranged in a timeline to reflect the group's activities from its beginnings until 2010, when the group's end is announced.
The participants' stage costumes, musical instruments, awards and concert recordings will also be shown, as well as other things that have not yet been seen by the wider public, reflecting the creative activity of the group "Līvi".
The exhibition will be supplemented with items from the collection of the Museum of Liepāja.
The visual design of the exhibition was created in collaboration with fashion artist and painter Elita Patmalnieci.
Musicians who were associated with the group "Livy" and their relatives also responded to the invitation and shared objects and memories.
The origins of "Livu" can be traced back to 1972, when a vocal instrumental ensemble led by Juris Pavītols was created in the Liepāja House of Culture.
In its original composition, the ensemble participated in the festival "Liepaja amber" in 1972 and 1974, as well as in city and republic shows.
In 1976, a fateful meeting took place when Juris Pavītols met Eric Kīgelis and founded a group in the Metalurgs Palace of Culture, inviting Ingrīda Gūtmane, Andris Krūziņš and Jāni Grodums to join.
Over the years, the band's lineup has changed several times.
Members have joined, some have left, some have returned.
However, the most important thing - the desire to prove that Latvian rock music is able to live and exist - has remained unchanged.
"With jeans, hair, and a beard, these guys were a far cry from the stereotypical showgirl", says music critic Klaus Wowere of the group.
In addition to the aforementioned musicians, the group has worked with such outstanding musicians as Igo, Vilnis Rusiņš, Modris Sterns, Valdis Stark, Laimis Racenajs, Tālis Pusbarnieks, Ainars Virga, Aivars Brīz, Guntars Mucenieks, Dainis Virga, Thomas Klein and many others.
Admission to the exhibition is free.
The exhibition runs from 19 August to 30 October.
On 27 August, the 40th anniversary celebration of the group "Līvi" will be held at the "Pūt, vējiņi" concert hall in Liepāja.
