Eggs contain the metabolic nutrient choline, and bell peppers are a good source of vitamin C.
Adequate intake of these nutrients can reduce cortisol levels and thus the accumulation of fat around the midsection.
Oatmeal with fresh berries is another tasty, fat-burning breakfast to add to your menu.
Oat bran and berries contain solvents that, according to Canadian researchers, control the appetite-stimulating hormone ghrelin and thus the feeling of hunger.
Berries also contain polyphenols, which aid weight loss and prevent the buildup of fat.
Vegetables and protein can also do wonders for weight loss.
This combination can create a sense of home.
Vegetables contain water and fiber, so they add a sense of home.
At the same time, protein slows down the digestive process and makes you feel full for longer.
For lunch, you can have chicken salad or a protein shake with your favorite vegetables.
Which combinations of products to avoid.
Fruits contain sugars - either monosaccharides or disaccharides - made up of one or two molecules.
Starch, on the other hand, is a polysaccharide found in vegetables.
While the fruit is broken down mechanically in the stomach, it is not broken down chemically until the third or fourth stage of digestion in the intestines.
The starch is broken down into three different stages, starting in the mouth.
Therefore, it is important not to eat sugary foods immediately after a meal.
When you eat sweet food immediately after a meal, it is "trapped" in the stomach along with other food, where it is not chemically digested and begins to spoil.
Do not eat bread, potatoes, peas, bananas, dates, or other carbohydrates with lemons, limes, oranges, grapefruits, pineapples, or other sour fruits.
The enzyme ptyalin, found in saliva, works only in an alkaline environment.
Fruit acids not only inhibit the digestion of carbohydrates but also promote their fermentation.
Do not eat combinations of eggs and meat, nuts and meat, cheese and eggs, or cheese and nuts, meat and milk, eggs and milk, or nuts and milk and similar protein-rich foods at the same meal.
Their digestion requires different digestive juices, each with a different strength, characteristics and time of arrival in the stomach.
Watermelon, honeydew melon, nutmeg and other melons should always be eaten separately from other foods.
Melons are not digested if they are in the stomach with other foods.
Fat combined with protein-rich products.
Fat works well with starch, but the same cannot be said of fat and protein - fat inhibits protein digestion.
Protein can be combined with a very small amount of fat.
If you eat a lot of protein, avoid fat altogether.
This also applies to freshness - it is not advisable to combine a large amount of nuts (containing protein) with a whole avocado (containing fat).
This combination prevents effective weight loss.
What's the best way to cook?
"Cooking and heat treatment cause a significant loss of nutrients - about 15% to 55% of the original nutrient content of the products", says the nutritionist.
Most nutrients are lost when food is cooked in water.
However, the nutritional value of some foods is enhanced by cooking.
It is best to use the liquid left after cooking vegetables to make soup - this will preserve the nutrients that remain in the water and will allow you to eat them later.
Vegetables should also be cooked by steaming.
Heat treatment significantly increases the bioavailability of lycopene in tomatoes.
Cooking tomatoes for 30 minutes increases the lycopene content by 25%.
Heat treatment also significantly increases the bioavailability of beta-carotene, which is found in red, yellow and orange plants such as tomatoes, carrots, sweet potatoes and spinach.
The heat treatment of eggs and meat removes the natural characteristics of their proteins, making them more easily digestible.
Similarly, heat treatment of meat and eggs makes the iron and other minerals contained in these products more easily absorbed by the body.
It should also be borne in mind that freezing may reduce the vitamin C content by between 10% and 90%, while freezing the solvent has no effect.
Beans in combination with tomatoes can increase the body's absorption of iron, which in turn improves brain and muscle function.
Our bodies absorb up to 33% less non-heme iron from plant foods such as beans, leafy greens and cereals than heme iron from animal products such as beef, fish and chicken.
You can greatly increase your body's absorption of non-haem iron by eating non-haem iron products with sources of vitamin C such as oranges, tomatoes and berries.
Vitamin C helps to change non-haem iron so that it is more easily absorbed by our body.
Iron is needed for the production of hemoglobin, which carries oxygen to muscles and the brain.
To get the most benefit from your salad, add healthy fats, such as olive or linseed oil.
When making salmon sandwiches, add vitamin-D-rich salmon or sardines to unsweetened yogurt, which is a good source of calcium.
