Central Command, known as Centcom, is a military base in Tampa, Florida that oversees U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
The latest news about this report is that the intelligence reports, confirmed by senior Centcom leaders, painted a more positive picture of the U.S. fight against terrorism than was actually the case.
Ken Calvert, a Republican representative from California, says: "The actions of the Centcom are unacceptable - it is our soldiers who suffer when our policymakers are misinformed".
CENTCOM's management failures are to be found at the highest levels of the organisation.
This 10-page report details challenges in Central Command's reporting and analysis of U.S. efforts to train Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While this does not provide conclusive evidence that senior Obama administration officials ordered the redactions, it does suggest that Centcom leadership has put some pressure on analysts to paint a more optimistic picture of the threat posed by the Islamic State (also known as ISIS or ISIL).
The report states that in the first half of 2015, press releases, statements and reports of the Central Command to Congress portrayed the situation in a significantly more positive light than it actually was.
For example, Centcom representatives have publicly stated that the operation to retake Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul is the second largest city in Iraq still under the control of the Islamic State.
Republican Representative Mike Pompeo of Kansas reported: "A months-long investigation makes this abundantly clear".
Between mid-2014 and mid-2015, senior U.S. Central Command officials distorted reports to portray the ISIS threat in Iraq as less than it actually was.
The Republican Party formed a task force after learning that analysts feared information about the Islamic State was being distorted.
As the investigation continues, new revelations in the case will follow Thursday's report.
The Department of Defense Inspector General conducts investigations of Centcom's intelligence activities.
The Democratic members of the Intelligence Oversight Committee released their own report Thursday in which they agree with some of the conclusions of the Republican task force.
In his report, Representative Adams B. Schiff, a Democrat, says that from 2014 to 2015, Centcom was too restricted in its ability to produce intelligence assessment reports on ISIS and the Iraqi Security Forces.
Mr. Schiff explains that this process "stopped the flow of information", undermined the analysts' work ethic, and "spread false facts".
But Schiff and the Democrats added that there is no evidence that the White House pressured Centcom analysts to produce reports according to "a predetermined or political agenda".
The Daily Beast published the preliminary results of the congressional inquiry on Thursday.
In August, The New York Times reported that the Pentagon's inspector general was investigating complaints by Centcom analysts.
A Pentagon spokesman, Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, said the Pentagon would not comment on the congressional report pending an investigation.
He also added that experts sometimes interpret complex data differently, and the Department of Defense and the Intelligence Community encourage a constructive dialogue on vital national security issues.
The inquiry is not limited to the question of whether the US-led bombing campaign in Iraq and Syria is succeeding (a question raised by a growing number of Defence Department officials).
But accusations over the past year have raised questions about whether President Obama can fully trust the Central Command's reports on military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan and other hot spots.
Criticism of the Islamic State's spying harks back to more than a decade ago, when Centcom intelligence analyst Gregory Hooker published a study claiming that the George W. Bush administration launched the war in Afghanistan with too little thought to its possible consequences.
Hooker also played a significant role in exposing the Islamic State's spying.
