The most depressing food to eat during a depression is a hearty meal
In March of 1933, shortly after his inauguration, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat down in the Oval Office for a meal.
President Roosevelt enjoyed such delicacies as foie gras and Maryland turtle soup.
On this occasion, however, his meal was much more modest - scrambled eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes, and plum pudding.
Says Jane Ziegelman: "It's a way of showing solidarity in cooking for people who have had a really hard time".
Her husband, Andrew Kou, adds: "It's also a message to Americans about how they should eat".
There's a couple in Brooklyn Heights who are food historians.
Kou's latest book, The Garden Fury, describes Chinese cuisine in America, while Ziegelman, in his book 97 Apples, describes life through food in a tenement on Manhattan's Lower East Side.
Their new collaborative work, "A Satisfying Meal", to be published Tuesday by Harper, is the story of American food during the Great Depression.
In a show of culinary solidarity, they shared a meal together at Eisenberg's Sandwich Shop, a humble lunch spot in the Flatiron District that dates back to 1929, the start of the Great Depression.
Mrs. Ziegelmann, 54, ordered a sandwich with melted cheese and chopped olives, while Kou, 57, ordered a turkey, mashed potato and vegetable salad.
When the reporter ordered the fake bunny, the couple admitted that his choice was very appropriate for a conversation about food during the Great Depression.
Mrs. Siegelman said that the fake bunny was very popular.
There was the peanut gallery, the liver gallery, and the bean gallery.
They were made from the basic ingredient and other ingredients that enriched the meal.
Imagine what it would be like to eat enough peanuts to replace your lunch.
Mr. Koo was stunned.
"It must have felt like my stomach was full of lead", he added.
In the years before the Depression, the American dinner table was a smorgasbord, especially in rural areas.
The women cooked meals for their male workers and served freshly made soups for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
During World War I, it was the Americans who sent food to Europe. "The Full Meal" describes how Americans adapted to a time when America was suddenly no longer a land of plenty.
"At that time, food was becoming the main focus of the American people's daily lives", says Mr. Kou, explaining why he and his wife wanted to write about this particular subject.
Equally important were the new budget diets, in which unfamiliar foods such as fake rabbit and stir-fries became common, stir-fries being "a great way to use up leftovers", said Ziegelmann, because chefs could hide unattractive ingredients under a creamy sauce.
Cheap dried fruit replaced fresh fruit.
Meat, long a staple of American meals, was now an extremely rare luxury.
At a time when the number of calories and the nutritional value of food were more important than taste, new, never-before-seen formations were born.
In an old cookbook, Mrs. Ziegelmann found recipes for onions stuffed with peanut butter.
Mr. Kou adds: "It was not a popular addition to the dinner table".
"It was surreal", says Siegelman.
Peanut butter and fried onions don't mix.
Many homemade recipes are suitable for times of hardship.
Household economists such as Louise Stanley, head of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943, determined the nation's eating habits, which had not been experienced before or since the Great Depression.
By publishing articles and recipes in newspapers and magazines, they encouraged housewives to become "economists" and take on such challenges as turning a pasta and carrot mixture into a tasty meal.
The Satisfying Meal is a feast of historical delights.
Particularly interesting is evidence of the government's attitude toward its starving citizens, such as President Herbert Hoover's "let me eat cake" attitude.
Although in public he talked about his humble upbringing and eating in Iowa, in reality he ate like the refined millionaire he had become.
"He enjoyed European dishes, such as fish and cucumber sauce", says Mr. Ko.
He ate in a near-gilded hotel room wearing a dinner jacket.
He was completely out of touch with reality.
President Roosevelt would have made the same mistake if his wife, Eleanor, had not urged him to set an example with his eating habits.
Roosevelt hired a housekeeper who did not know how to cook, and the White House became a place "where not only was some of the worst food in Washington served, but the worst food was cooked", says the book.
As the nation's economy recovered, most of the Depression-era culinary traditions disappeared.
But we continue to focus on calories and nutrition, as well as the application of science to cooking, added Ms. Ziegelman.
The couple said that writing the book helped them to understand more about Mrs. Ziegelman's mother's eating habits, such as her inability to throw away food.
"She was really afraid to throw out the food", said Mr. Kou.
Ms. Siegelman said, "She was really upsetting people".
There was an incident with a windmill once.
While we were eating at the Eisenberg Diner, a couple of the writers pulled out of their bag a homemade dessert: plum pudding, which President Roosevelt used to eat for lunch.
"It's a feather duster", said Mrs. Ziegelmann, adding that it was a common practice at the time to call modest dishes chic.
It contains no powder, just prunes, a little flour, sugar, water, and cinnamon.
Everyone eagerly dipped their chopsticks into the brown mass on the plates.
Surprisingly, it wasn't that bad.
Mr. Koo ate a few more dumplings.
Following the advice of an experienced "economist", he said to his wife: "Grind the hazelnuts a little".
