State-owned energy company Latvenergo is following the process of opening up the gas market from the perspective of both a consumer and a potential trader, the company's press secretary Ivita Bider said.
'Latvenergo's decision whether to enter the gas market as a trader in the future will depend on the gas market model and legal framework that will be created.'
"That is why we are actively involved in drafting and commenting on legislation and making our own proposals", explains Bider.
The BNS agency has already written that the Ministry of Economy (EM), in cooperation with the Public Services Regulatory Commission and the energy company Latvijas Gāze, has developed a draft Cabinet Regulation "Regulations for the Trading and Use of Natural Gas" that will change the operating principles of the existing natural gas market by ensuring the right of natural gas users to freely choose a natural gas trader from 3 April 2017.
In working towards a new natural gas market regulation, the EU aims to make the process of natural gas trading as simple and user-friendly as possible.
Therefore, the 'trader-centric model' was chosen as the most efficient and user-friendly service solution, where all customer-related activities are provided by the trader, with one contract, one invoice and one information and customer service point, leaving the technical aspects of the natural gas distribution system to the distribution system operator.
A similar solution is currently being implemented in electricity trading.
It is recalled that there is a gradual opening of the market for household customers: even after 3 April 2017, household customers who do not wish to switch supplier will be able to continue to receive natural gas from an existing supplier at a regulated price, thus becoming connected customers.
'In this case, the obligation to supply natural gas to connected users at a regulated price is imposed on the public trader', the Ministry informed.
On the other hand, traders will have to choose a natural gas trader with whom to conclude a natural gas trading contract.
Until the conclusion of the contract for the sale of natural gas, natural gas will be sold to traders for a certain period of time by the existing natural gas trader at a price determined by him.
The draft Cabinet Regulation discusses in detail the rights and obligations of natural gas traders, system operators and users.
The rules shall lay down the arrangements for the supply and the interruption of the supply of natural gas to customers, the requirements for the safe use of the natural gas system, the rights and obligations of the trader, the public trader, the system operator, the user and the owner of the gas installation with regard to the supply and use of natural gas, the arrangements for the settlement of accounts for services received, the rates of default interest, the arrangements for the switching of traders and the supply of customers in the event of disruption of the supply of natural gas, and the arrangements for the supply of natural gas to connected customers by the public trader.
