The turnover of the canning company Blue Lagoon fell by 33,8% last year.
The turnover of the canned food producer "Blue Lagoon" last year was 4,202 million euros, which is 33.8% less than a year earlier, while the company's losses decreased 5.7 times to 904,7 thousand euros, according to the annual financial report published in the database "Lursoft".
The management report of the company states that in 2015 the company operated at a loss due to several reasons, including a persistent lack of working capital caused by the exit of Unicredit Bank from the Baltic market, terminating the previously existing credit line and leaving the Blue Lagoon with concluded contracts without the possibility to execute them.
Consequently, the company did not have sufficient funds to purchase cheaper raw materials in large quantities and benefit from a volume discount.
The bank's withdrawal from the Latvian market also prevented the company from implementing projects supported by the European Union Structural Funds, which would have enabled the yard to acquire new production equipment and modernise its infrastructure.
The company's financial generators were also negatively affected last year by the increase in raw material prices and the reluctance of customers to pay more for the company's products.
'Only in the second half of July 2016 customers recognised the price change and were ready to buy at the new - higher - prices', the company's management states.
In addition, the Commission expressed doubts as to the compatibility of the measures with the internal market, in particular as regards their compatibility with the internal market under Article 107 (3) (c) TFEU.
The investors have already visited the company's largest creditor, UniCredit Leasing, where the parties have met and discussed possible investment plans.
On the basis of the above, the Commission concludes that the restructuring plan ensures the restoration of the long-term viability of the Bank.
This plan included the improvement and optimisation of technological processes to achieve higher productivity and production capacity.
'Several machines have been purchased to increase the production speed', the company's management stated.
The management of the Blue Lagoon notes that the equipment purchased in 2016 will allow the company's plant to fulfil orders that were previously not possible.
The first production batch to be produced on this equipment will be ready in August.
Since the MoUs for the sale of the product have already been signed, all production will be sold in accordance with the MoUs.
The new product will increase turnover by approximately EUR 300 thousand per month,' the company's management states.
The company also plans to sign a cooperation agreement for the supply of fish products to Iraq in August 2016.
Blue Lagoon has shipped its first experimental container to Israel in 2016, expanded its sales market to Cyprus and will sign a cooperation agreement with a new supermarket chain in the US this September.
As a result of all the above measures, the company plans to increase its turnover.
In 2014, the Blue Lagoon operated with a turnover of EUR 6,347 million and a loss of EUR 5,113 million.
Blue Lagoon was founded in 1997 and has a share capital of EUR 1,156 million.
The company is owned by two Latvian individuals - Mihail Kaidanov (89,11%) and Igor Shirshon (10,89%).
