A man is forced to leave his home because of a neighbor's construction project.
LTV's Studio 4 spoke with Dmitry Saydyashev, whose neighbor has started a major renovation of his apartment.
The problem is that my neighbors did some illegal construction, and my apartment has a broken ceiling.
Then I informed the Riga Building Committee, the building manager, and other organizations.
The building department said we're not an operations department and we don't have any experts.
"The owner has to go to the Latvian Association of Engineers, and an expert will be there", says Dmitry.
The expert arrived, verified the situation and concluded that the cladding was in poor condition.
However, a month has passed since Dmitry first filed a complaint with the building department, and as of early this week, no one has been able to say whether his apartment is safe.
The housing authority said, that's the law, wait, if you're not happy, write to everyone in turn.
"Then I wrote to the Riga City Council, but they forwarded the letter to the building manager, who then sent it back to the building committee, and that was the end of it", says Dmitry.
After reviewing all the paperwork, it's clear that the construction has been halted, although every once in a while you can hear someone working there.
An expert's report was due within two months, and the owner of the apartment, who was carrying out the repairs, had six months in which to remedy the defects.
The independent expert has drawn up his report, but the Municipality considers it incomplete and superficial.
The expert has not indicated whether the metal grating in this load-bearing structure is damaged, so there is no certainty that the occupant of the apartment below is endangered.
"That is why we have requested additional explanations from this expert", says Ilze Žuka, a representative of the Riga City Building Department.
Despite a ban on any repairs on the top floor, the construction continues.
The fine for building without a building permit ranges from 70 to 700 euros, but it can be much higher.
Pending the expert's report, the building committee has decided that both apartments - the one being built and Dmitry's - should be condemned.
"This is an unprecedented case in the practice of the building authority, when in this way, due to their ignorance or simply unwillingness, residents may have endangered not only their own property, but also the owner of the property below, as a result of which this owner cannot exploit his property", says a representative of the building authority.
Now Dmitry has to find another place to live - with relatives, friends, a hotel, or another apartment.
But Dmitry could try to recover damages from his neighbor in a civil suit, which could take a very long time.
Because of the arbitrary construction, both apartments are currently off-limits to the public until the developer gives his approval, which can take up to three weeks.
The owner of the dwelling where the repair work was carried out will be liable for damages.
The owner of this apartment is also facing up to six months in prison for failing to comply with a court order.
