NASA climate model: Venus was once a habitable planet
According to NASA's latest climate models, Venus was once a habitable planet.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model to explore the history of Venus using tools and algorithms that are also used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, which has a hot, waterless surface and an atmosphere composed almost entirely of carbon, ever had conditions similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have previously suggested that Venus' slow rotation rate could be explained by its thick atmosphere.
But recent simulations suggest that Venus once had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere and that it rotated slowly.
The model also looks at the early topography of Venus.
It had more dry land than Earth, but it had enough water and geographic diversity to support life and keep the water from evaporating.
In the early days of Venus, the Sun was 30 percent brighter.
In a GISS model simulation of the rotation of Venus, the model reveals that the daylight portion lasts for 2 months, explained GISS scientist Antonio Del Genio in a press release.
This process heats the planet's surface and produces rain, which in turn forms thick cloud layers that act like an umbrella, shielding the planet from the sun's heat.
The result is a temperate climate temperature that is actually several degrees lower than the temperature on Earth today.
The model depicts the history of Venus, which is similar to the theory of evolution developed by scientists in their hypotheses.
Although once habitable, Venus has been subjected to extreme heat and ultraviolet radiation for billions of years.
Its oceans evaporated, and the reefs were scorched by ultraviolet rays.
When the water evaporated completely, all that was left was a thin atmosphere of carbon dioxide, a deadly greenhouse gas - the Venus we know today.
Scientists have published the results of a new climate model for Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
