Kepler measures the rotation rate of stars in the Pleiades star cluster.
The latest mission of the Kepler telescope has helped astronomers compile the most complete catalog of the rotation rates of stars in the Pleiades star cluster.
The new data are helping astronomers to understand why the stars in this cluster rotate at different speeds and how the rotation rate of the stars is related to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with those of other stars, we can learn more about the relationship between a star's mass, its age, and even the history of its solar system", says Luis Rebula, a scientist at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, California.
The Pleiades star is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in this cluster are just beginning to mature, reaching an age of about 125 million years.
They're spinning as fast as they can.
As they swirl around at top speed, these growing stars give off huge amounts of stellar wind.
When the winds hit the star's magnetic field, they slow the star down.
Stars slow down as they age.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by determining the time between the appearance of a recognizable region of stars, such as sunspots.
A recent catalog of rotation rates shows that larger stars rotate more slowly than smaller ones.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, with taller dancers doing pirouettes more slowly than shorter ones.
Rebull explains that the Pleiades "ballet" shows that slow-spinning objects are larger and more massive, while faster-spinning objects are very small stars.
Because the Pleiades star is so close, it serves as a great space laboratory for comparing stellar characteristics with rotation speeds.
Rebull explains that the Pleiades star helps to establish theoretical models for the rotation of stars in both directions, both older and younger.
We still have much to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down and stop spinning.
Rebull and his colleagues detailed their analysis of the rotation rates of Pleiades stars in three new papers soon to be published in the Astronomy Journal.
